column37: Mostly by personal knowledge. Some background informations was given by GPT. GPT was only used to comfirm some scientific facts.
I use it to have more understanding of the circumstances and choices.

I first asked GPT to evaluate the task on its own, then I asked it to evaluate my own answer. I then asked follow-up questions regrading the differences in our answers. If I find GPT's argument to be convincing enough, I included it in my final answer.

I first asked it to answer the question for me, but then it's answer did't make any sense to me. It did not consider that there is no oxygen on the moon's surface, and it did not change it's answer even after I pointed it to the system.

I couldn't really use the given GPT because every time I sent it a text, it showed that there was an error. I think it still needs some improvement before it can really help other people. Thanks to the team for their hard work; keep going on. I wish you very good luck！

In terms of the most important message (what should be prioritized) I choose to accept GPT's suggestions by raising questions to him and confirming. For the information that is less crucial (e.g. nylon and pistol), I rank them by myself.

First, we get overall ranking from gpt and then from my opinions and belief to rank, I rank the items and ask gpt if my belief is correct. Though gpt disagrees with me, its explanation is reliable and I use my choice.

I just let it list the order for me and asked some questions why it thought that item was important and more important than other things.

Give him the relevant requirements,then send him the article,and finally check the answer

I asked GPT what is the most important thing to survive, then what is the next thing, the third thing until the last important thing. When I have doubts about the answer, I asked about my concern then take the message.

At first I asked GPT to help me rank the 15 items provided with all the information given in the task, as well as asking it for reasons on why it chose particular ranks. While most responses were sensible, the low ranking for oxygen made me question the responses, which is why I decided to take a closer look at all items and sort them based on my own knowledge as well as the reasons GPT provided.
according to the request,i ask gpt to help me rank 15 items and ask if it can explain its ranking reason to me.then i adjust the answer.

From a first ranking list, I made it more readable and then tried to refine it step by step by providing my personal insights to end with a final ranking list.

There are quite a number of assumptions made by GPT which rendered its reasoning and ranking of the tools based on importance to be less logical than the ranking placed by a regular human being with sufficient knowledge about space. Given my background in space science and astrophysics, I have to make some assumptions too which I had clarified with the organiser of this event. Given the assumptions made, I've placed my own ranking of the tools while comparing the ranking given by GPT and its reasons.
I read the task and tried shortly explain to chat what do I need to do. It wrote me ranking, I doubted some points and it gave me some arguments why is this or that point is at this or that place.

it just gives a satisfying answer in the first attempt. but still, ask it to refine itself or double-check its answer reaches perfection.
show the situation and the items to GPT, ask she to order them. Then discuss with her about some controversial points. Finally output the list and order.

I fed the information of the scenario to GPT, then asked it to rank the items on the list based on most important for survival. GPT gave a list together with detailed explanations.
The answers that were provided made sense

I relied somewhat on GPT, but I ultimately didn't agree with many of its answers, from what I know about the moon. It prioritized matches very highly, but fire is not sustainable on the moon due to it not having an atmosphere. Additionally, I didn't think signal flares would work well either, as again, that relies on combustion which is very limited on the moon. I also disagreed with GPT and thought that oxygen should be prioritized much higher -- 200 miles is a long distance to travel, and astronauts should not risk travelling on low oxygen.

By asking GPT the question.
I trusted it gave the accurate results

I for the most part agreed with GPT's assessment of the situation, but I needed clarity on a few things. I don't have a lot of knowledge about this subject, so I had to put a lot more trust into GPT than I typically would.
I arrived at my final answer ranking by thinking of what you need to best survive in space. I didn't feel I needed GPT's help so i did not use it
It seems to not have sufficient skill to evaluate the situation. It ignores the part about the damaged spacecraft and the 200 mile trek, and makes lots of assumptions
I asked it what some of the important aspects of surviving on the moon was. Then I asked it what I would need and it told me.

I asked GPT questions about how some items can be used and how important it would be compared to other items. It was able to give me an overview of how things can be used and how it can help the situation.

I inputted the prompt into GPT and read through its answer and reasoning, then asked it to summarize the explanation into a list of the 15 items. I then ranked the items on the task sheet according to GPT's list.

I put the instructions and task in the gpt, then i read their answer. I reordered the first two ranks on my own based on personal opinion, but kept most of gpt's ranking the same in my submission because the reasoning they gave made sense.
I asked the AI about what the conditions were like on the moon and how I could utilize each item. I used this information to rank the list of tools.
I mostly copied the ChatGPT output and then kind of extrapolated the rest
I told GPT to give me its ranking, considering all the available information. However, I disagreed with a lot of its reasoning, so I ultimately went with my own ranking.
